---
import { Image } from "astro:assets";
import PNotes from "../components/PNotes.astro";
import mcp from "../img/mcp-nobg.png";
import wtf from "../img/wtf.jpeg";
---

<p-slide class="center" autoplay timing="550">
  <h2 style="margin-block-end: 0.2em" class="main-gradient">
    Let's talk about MCP
  </h2>
  <p-fragment
    ><Image
      src={mcp}
      alt="mcp logo"
      class="alter-image-size"
      style="--image-start-size: 9em"
    /></p-fragment
  >
</p-slide>
<p-slide>
  <ul style="line-height: 1.8em">
    <li>
      🐣 <span class="main-sub-gradient">Introduced in 2024 by Anthropic</span>
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from left">
      📋 <span class="main-sub-gradient">An open standard protocol</span>
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from right">
      🔌 <span class="main-sub-gradient"
        >Connects AI apps to tools and data</span
      >
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from below">
      🔒 <span class="main-sub-gradient"
        >Permission-based integration model</span
      >
    </li>
  </ul>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      MCP stands for "Model Context Protocol". It is an open standard introduced
      by Anthropic in November 2024 to standardize how AI applications connect
      to external tools, data sources, and services.
    </p>
    <p>
      The idea is similar to having a common interface: instead of building a
      custom integration for every AI application and every external system,
      developers can expose capabilities through MCP servers, while AI
      applications act as MCP clients.
    </p>
    <p>
      MCP does not automatically make every integration fully isolated or secure
      by itself. Security depends on the host application, the client, the
      server implementation, and the permissions granted by the user. However,
      it gives developers a standard way to structure these integrations and
      reason about the boundary between the AI application and external systems.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>
<p-slide class="center" autoplay timing="550">
  <h1 class="main-gradient">Why MCP?</h1>
  <p-fragment
    ><Image
      src={wtf}
      alt="wtf image"
      class="alter-image-size"
      style="border-radius: 1em"
    /></p-fragment
  >
</p-slide>
<p-slide>
  <ul style="line-height: 1.8em">
    <li>
      🌍 <span class="main-sub-gradient">AI apps need the outside world</span>
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from left">
      📁 <span class="main-sub-gradient"
        >Files, APIs, databases, docs, CRMs...</span
      >
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from right">
      🧩 <span class="main-sub-gradient"
        >Every system exposes data differently</span
      >
    </li>
  </ul>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      AI applications are powerful, but they become much more useful when they
      can interact with external systems: files, APIs, databases, repositories,
      internal documentation, CRMs, and many other sources of information.
    </p>

    <p>
      The problem is that each external system exposes data and actions in a
      different way. Every API has its own structure, authentication model,
      permissions, and data format.
    </p>

    <p>
      This is the starting point: AI apps need context and actions from the real
      world, but the real world is fragmented.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>
<p-slide>
  <h2 class="main-gradient">The N x M problem</h2>

  <ul style="line-height: 1.8em">
    <li>
      🤖 <span class="main-sub-gradient">N AI apps</span>
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from right">
      🔌 <span class="main-sub-gradient">M tools and data sources</span>
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="zoom">
      📈 <span class="main-sub-gradient">N x M custom integrations</span>
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from below">
      🧯 <span class="main-sub-gradient">Complexity grows fast</span>
    </li>
  </ul>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      Without a shared protocol, each AI application has to build its own
      integration with each external tool or data source.
    </p>

    <p>
      If we have N AI applications and M tools, we quickly end up with an N by M
      integration problem. The more apps and tools we add, the more custom
      connections we have to build and maintain.
    </p>

    <p>This is expensive, repetitive, and hard to scale.</p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>
<p-slide>
  <h2><span class="main-gradient">The deterministic problem</span> 🔢</h2>
</p-slide>
<p-slide>
  <ul style="line-height: 1.8em">
    <li>
      🎲 <span class="main-sub-gradient">LLMs are probabilistic</span>
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from left">
      🧠 <span class="main-sub-gradient">They generate likely answers</span>
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from right">
      🧾 <span class="main-sub-gradient">Tools need precise inputs</span>
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="zoom">
      ⚠️ <span class="main-sub-gradient">APIs expect deterministic calls</span>
    </li>
  </ul>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      There is another important problem: AI models are probabilistic. They do
      not execute code in the traditional sense, and they do not naturally
      behave like deterministic software.
    </p>

    <p>
      A model predicts the most likely next tokens based on the conversation and
      its context. This is incredibly useful for language, reasoning, and
      interpretation, but external systems usually need something much more
      precise.
    </p>

    <p>
      APIs, databases, file systems, and business tools expect deterministic
      calls: specific parameters, predictable structures, clear permissions, and
      well-defined execution boundaries.
    </p>

    <p>
      MCP helps by creating a structured layer between the probabilistic world
      of the model and the deterministic world of tools and systems.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>
<p-slide class="center">
  <h2 class="main-gradient">The MCP solution</h2>
</p-slide>
<p-slide>
  <ul style="line-height: 1.8em">
    <li>
      🔌 <span class="main-sub-gradient">Build the connection once</span>
    </li>
    <p-fragment>
      <li>
        🔁 <span class="main-sub-gradient">Reuse it across AI applications</span
        >
      </li>
    </p-fragment>
    <p-fragment>
      <li>
        📋 <span class="main-sub-gradient">Use a shared protocol</span>
      </li>
    </p-fragment>
    <p-fragment>
      <li>
        ✨ <span class="main-sub-gradient">The “USB-C for AI apps” idea</span>
      </li>
    </p-fragment>
  </ul>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      The goal of MCP is to avoid rebuilding the same kind of integration again
      and again.
    </p>

    <p>
      A tool can expose its capabilities through an MCP server, and different AI
      applications can connect to it through the same protocol.
    </p>

    <p>
      This is why MCP is often described as a sort of USB-C for AI applications:
      not because it removes all complexity, but because it introduces a shared
      connector between AI apps and external systems.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>
